6. Proactive Agent Design

This is the key differentiator.

The system must not wait for prompts. It should:

Trigger Conditions
	•	New high-priority email
	•	Cloud alert
	•	Cost spike
	•	SLA breach
	•	Security incident
	•	Calendar conflict
	•	Unanswered customer email

Behavior Model

Tier 1 – Suggest
	•	Draft response
	•	Summarize issue
	•	Propose action

Tier 2 – Auto-Execute (Low Risk)
	•	Tag emails
	•	Schedule tentative meetings
	•	Create internal tickets
	•	Notify relevant teams

Tier 3 – Approval Required
	•	Send external emails
	•	Modify cloud infrastructure
	•	Delete resources
	•	Close security alerts
	•	Change IAM policies

⸻

7. Security Model (Enterprise-Grade)

A. Identity
	•	Azure AD as primary IdP
	•	Conditional access policies
	•	Device trust enforcement
	•	SCIM provisioning
	•	Role-based access control

⸻

B. Least Privilege Everywhere
	•	Per-tenant isolation
	•	Per-user access scopes
	•	No global admin mode
	•	Time-bound tokens
	•	Scoped service principals

⸻

C. Prompt Injection Mitigation
	•	Label all external email content as untrusted
	•	Strip executable instructions from emails
	•	Tool invocation schema validation
	•	Context segmentation (system vs user vs external data)
	•	Two-layer planning system:
	•	Model A interprets input
	•	Model B executes tool plans

⸻

D. Cloud Safety Controls

For Azure and GCP:
	•	Read-only default mode
	•	Change freeze windows
	•	Action budgets
	•	Dual approval for destructive actions
	•	IAM modification lock
	•	Activity anomaly detection

⸻

E. Skill / Extension Model (Future Phase)

Do NOT open third-party plugin marketplace at launch.

Phase 1:
	•	First-party tools only.

Phase 2:
	•	Signed extensions
	•	Capability manifest
	•	Isolated execution
	•	Manual enterprise approval

